---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="Principles — Wayfinders" description="The promises everyone in Wayfinders makes to each other.">
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Principles of engagement</h1>
    <p class="intro">
      The promises everyone in Wayfinders makes to each other. Mentees, mentors, and Ben. Read this before applying. Read it again at the start of session 1.
    </p>
    <p class="intro">
      These are not aspirations. They are the conditions of taking part.
    </p>

    <hr />

    <h2>1. What's said here, stays here</h2>
    <p>
      Anything shared in a session, in the cohort group, or in the alumni network is confidential by default. You can take what you've learned into your own life, but you don't carry someone else's story out without their explicit permission.
    </p>
    <p>
      This includes employer names, salary figures, family situations, spiritual struggles, and the contents of the decision someone is sitting with.
    </p>
    <p>
      The only exception: if someone discloses harm to themselves or others, that's a safeguarding matter and the rules change.
    </p>

    <h2>2. Honest, not impressive</h2>
    <p>
      Wayfinders only works if people bring the actual decision, not the sanitised version. Bring the bit you don't want your church to know about. Bring the doubt. Bring the salary you wish wasn't so attractive.
    </p>
    <p>
      Mentors model this first. If a mentor can't be honest about their own moves, the mentees won't either.
    </p>

    <h2>3. Slow before fast</h2>
    <p>
      Discernment isn't a sprint. The cohort is eight weeks because that's roughly how long it takes for the question you arrived with to become the question you actually need to answer.
    </p>
    <p>
      Resist the urge to "solve" by session 2. Resist the urge to give advice in the first 20 minutes. Resist the urge to quote a Bible verse over a feeling.
    </p>

    <h2>4. The Bible is consulted, not weaponised</h2>
    <p>
      Scripture is a real source of counsel here. We read it together, we look for what it says about work, calling, money, and rest. We don't use it to shut down conversation or to make someone feel unfaithful for considering a "secular" choice.
    </p>
    <p>
      If you'd like the cohort to be more or less explicit about Scripture, that's a fair conversation to have in session 1. Wayfinders is broadly orthodox, evangelical-and-mainline friendly, with a high view of Scripture but no doctrinal litmus test.
    </p>

    <h2>5. Decisions over insights</h2>
    <p>
      The cohort exists to help you make a decision (or make peace with not making one yet). Insights are nice. Frameworks are nice. The test of a good cohort is whether people walk out of session 5 with a next step they can actually take on Monday morning.
    </p>
    <p>
      If the cohort is generating lots of insight and no decisions, something is off and we say so.
    </p>

    <h2>6. We don't do "God's perfect plan"</h2>
    <p>
      Wayfinders does not teach that there is one specific job God has preordained for you and your task is to guess what it is. We teach that God has given you wisdom, community, Scripture, and freedom, and that good decisions emerge from using them well.
    </p>
    <p>
      If "God's perfect plan" framing is what you're hoping for, this is probably not the right place. There's no judgement in that &mdash; it's just a different shape.
    </p>

    <h2>7. No upselling, ever</h2>
    <p>
      Wayfinders is free. Mentors are not paid. Ben is not paid. There is no premium tier, no follow-on coaching offer, no membership scheme, no upcharge for the alumni network.
    </p>
    <p>
      If anyone &mdash; including Ben &mdash; ever tries to commercialise this, that's a breach of the principles, and the cohort can call it out.
    </p>

    <h2>8. Show up</h2>
    <p>
      You said yes to five sessions and an application. Honour that. Tell your mentor in advance if you can't make a session. Tell the cohort if life is going sideways and you need a week off.
    </p>
    <p>
      Three missed sessions without contact and we'll have a kind conversation about whether this is the right time for you. We'd rather you came back to the spring cohort fresh than limped through this one.
    </p>

    <h2>9. We pray, lightly</h2>
    <p>
      We open and close sessions in prayer. Short, ordinary, no performance. If you'd rather not pray aloud, you don't have to. If prayer isn't part of your faith expression at the moment, say so &mdash; nobody will pretend you said amen when you didn't.
    </p>

    <h2>10. We're allowed to disagree</h2>
    <p>
      Christians disagree about work. About money. About ambition. About whether a sector is honourable. The cohort is for working that out in good company, not for arriving at the same answer.
    </p>
    <p>
      Mentors will sometimes give you their honest read. They will not tell you what to do.
    </p>

    <hr />

    <h2>What we ask in return</h2>
    <p>If Wayfinders is useful to you, we ask three things on the way out:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Stay in touch</strong> &mdash; the alumni network is the long-term shape of this.</li>
      <li><strong>Be the person who picks up the phone</strong> &mdash; when someone two cohorts behind you needs to talk through the same kind of decision, take the call.</li>
      <li><strong>Don't hoard it</strong> &mdash; tell other Christians it exists. Ideally before they're already drowning.</li>
    </ol>

    <div class="cta-block">
      <a href="/apply" class="btn">Apply for the autumn cohort</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</Base>

